Ghana Cocoa Premium Over Liffe Said to Have Risen in Three Weeks

-- B y   I s i s   A l m e i d a
-- 
2011-12-09T12:49:16Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-09/ghana-cocoa-premium-over-liffe-said-to-have-risen-in-three-weeks.html
The premium buyers are prepared to pay
in Europe for  cocoa beans  from Ghana, the world’s second-biggest
grower, rose over the past three weeks, according to four
traders with direct knowledge of the trade.  Ghanaian cocoa in the European market for delivery next
month is 85 pounds to 105 pounds ($133 to $165) a metric ton
above prices on the NYSE Liffe exchange in London, according to
the traders who declined to be identified because they’re not
authorized to speak to the media. Cocoa from Ghana was selling
at a premium of 80 pounds to 90 pounds three weeks ago, traders
said on Nov. 18.  Beans from  Ivory Coast , the biggest grower, are at a
premium of 55 pounds to 70 pounds above prices on NYSE Liffe,
three of the traders said. The premium was 75 pounds to 90
pounds three weeks ago, traders said on Nov. 18.  To contact the reporter on this story:
